\cf0 All of these tracers share a common origin: 
\f1\b massive stars with main-sequence ages of ~10
\f3 \uc0\u8311 
\f1 \'9610
\f3 \uc0\u8312 
\f1  years
\f0\b0 , born in molecular clouds, living and dying within a few hundred million years of their birth. This is what puts them firmly in the "young population" bucket and gives them their characteristic environmental properties (associated with star-forming gas, dust, metal-rich ISM).\
There's a subtle point worth being explicit about: 
\f1\b massive stars are not "metal-rich" by their own composition
\f0\b0  \'97 they form from whatever the local ISM looks like at the moment, and many Pop-I tracers have observed metallicities ranging from solar in MW spiral arms down to ~1/8 solar in metal-poor dwarf galaxies. But they form from gas that has been 
\f4\i recently
\f0\i0  enriched by previous generations, so as a 
\f4\i category
\f0\i0  they are metal-richer than typical Pop-II tracers. This matters for systematic budgets: Cepheids in metal-poor dwarf hosts have systematically different PLR slopes than Cepheids in MW-like hosts, and the metallicity correction is one of the largest residual systematics in the Pop-I rung.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

