\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Pop-I vs Pop-II vs systematic-cross-checking\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 This is worth being explicit about for your EDE work:\
The H
\f7 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  tension is sometimes characterized as "SH0ES disagrees with Planck." This is true but undersells the situation. The fuller statement is:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 "Multiple independent local methods (SH0ES Pop-I, Pop-II via SBF, MCP geometric, adh0cc geometric, and Mira) consistently give H
\f7 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  \uc0\u8776  73, while CMB-anchored \u923 CDM gives H
\f7 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  \uc0\u8776  67. The methods that prefer 73 use completely different stellar physics, completely different host populations, completely different photometric bands, and completely different calibration anchors. The persistence of the disagreement across this methodological diversity is what makes new physics in the early universe a more attractive resolution than astrophysical recalibration."\
Pop-I (via SH0ES) is the most precise component of this consensus, but it's not the entire argument. If SH0ES were the only high-H
\f7 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  measurement, the tension would be ~3\uc0\u963  at best and could plausibly be attributed to Cepheid systematics. The 5\u963 -plus tension comes from the 
\f1\b convergence
\f0\b0  of Pop-I, Pop-II, and geometric methods at H
\f7 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  ~ 73.\
}